Moralische Dilemmata for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents a massive bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses have continued to balloon in light of falling housing prices.
Now that the government has taken on complete responsibility for Fannies and Freddies' debts, American taxpayers will have to foot the bill for whatever is not covered by the insufficient funds of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in what is arguably the most capitalist country in the world?
Doesn't the time-honored principles of capitalism hold that those who believed in the real estate bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie should now accept the losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers now have to bear the burden of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be clear if the moral dilemmas of the current financial crisis were clearly defined.
But they are not.
Most importantly, it is unclear whether the bailout will ultimately cost U.S. taxpayers anything. It may prevent further systemic effects that could bring the financial sector and, consequently, the world economy to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
In addition, the securities issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as having an implicit guarantee from the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a rescue operation by the US government could undermine confidence in government securities and, due to their association with these, also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The global economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative booms and busts in asset values, which introduce questions of trust as well as fairness into the equation.
In many other countries, similar booms in the housing sector are coming to an end, and they might face the same trials – and the same moral dilemmas – that the US economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not just the housing markets.
The stock markets are too.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose by a factor of 5 in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost one-third of its value.
Similar highs and lows in stock markets have occurred in many other countries as well.
As long as they held, the preceding boom phases led to the overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a loss of confidence could grip the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some targeted bailouts might be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust; there is no way to predict how people will react when help is absent amid collapsing markets.
People's reactions to these events depend on their feelings and sense of justice.
The described booms and busts have caused a large redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested on the stock market or in the housing market fared well or poorly depending on the timing.
People will judge the fairness of these results based on what they were told and the implicit promises they inferred from it.
What were people in all these countries told about the markets they invested their money in?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
Es gibt leider keinen Weg, das herauszufinding.
Die Politik kann lediglich allgemein reagieren und nicht alle Fälle einzeln behandeln.
Wir wissen, dass das Wirtschaftswachstum der jüngsten Zeit in vielen Ländern spektakulär war.
Aber wurden die Kapitalanlagen in ihre Märkte zu teuer verkauft?
Haben zynische Verkäufer hier und anderswo die Menschen zu der Annahme verführt, dass die Boomzeiten Wohlstand für alle bringen würden?
Surely, there was a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – but most of the losers in this game are not struggling at the breadline.
Nevertheless, we cannot draw from this that one should allow them all their losses without qualification.
The nagging problem is one of "faith and trust".
National economies flourish only when "faith and trust" prevail.
The current situation, where speculative booms have driven the global economy – and now, after their collapse, are pushing it into recession – suggests that those who promoted certain investments did so against faith and trust.
Take the investors who bought the securities from Fannie and Freddie.
Although the US government never officially promised to bail them out, it established a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
